{
  "The dilution equation is:": "",
  "M1V2 = M2V1 (crossed subscripts)": "",
  "M1 + V1 = M2 + V2 (additive form)": "",
  "M1/V1 = M2/V2 (ratio form equation)": "",
  "M1V1 = M2V2 (standard dilution form)": "",
  "The dilution equation M1V1 = M2V2 shows that the product of initial concentration and volume equals the product of final concentration and volume, because the amount of solute stays constant.": "",
  "Dilution involves adding more:": "",
  "Another different solution to the mixture": "",
  "Solvent to reduce the concentration level": "",
  "Heat to evaporate some of the solvent out": "",
  "Solute to increase the concentration level": "",
  "Dilution is the process of adding more solvent to a solution to decrease its concentration while keeping the amount of solute the same.": "",
  "When you dilute a solution, the amount of solute:": "",
  "Increases as more solvent is added to it": "",
  "Doubles when the volume of solvent doubles": "",
  "Decreases as more solvent is added to it": "",
  "Stays the same because only solvent is added": "",
  "During dilution, only solvent is added. The amount of solute remains unchanged; only the concentration decreases because the solute is spread through more solvent.": "",
  "If 100 mL of 2 M solution is diluted to 200 mL, the new concentration is:": "",
  "4 M (the concentration doubled)": "",
  "1 M (the concentration was halved)": "",
  "2 M (the concentration is unchanged)": "",
  "0.5 M (the concentration quartered)": "",
  "Using M1V1 = M2V2: (2 M)(100 mL) = M2(200 mL). M2 = 200/200 = 1 M. Doubling the volume halves the concentration.": "",
  "Serial dilution is useful for:": "",
  "Heating solutions to very high temperatures quickly": "",
  "Removing solute from a solution using filtration": "",
  "Concentrating solutions by evaporating the solvent": "",
  "Creating very dilute solutions through repeated steps": "",
  "Serial dilution involves performing dilution steps repeatedly, each time diluting the previous solution. This allows scientists to reach very low concentrations precisely.": "",
  "What volume of 6 M HCl is needed to make 300 mL of 2 M HCl?": "",
  "300 mL of the stock solution is needed": "",
  "200 mL of the stock solution is needed": "",
  "50 mL of the stock solution is needed": "",
  "100 mL of the stock solution is needed": "",
  "M1V1 = M2V2: (6 M)(V1) = (2 M)(300 mL). V1 = 600/6 = 100 mL of the 6 M stock solution is needed.": "",
  "During dilution of acids, you should always:": "",
  "Freeze the solvent before adding the acid": "",
  "Heat the solution before diluting the acid": "",
  "Add water to the concentrated acid slowly": "",
  "Add acid to water, never water to acid": "",
  "When diluting acids, always add acid to water. Adding water to concentrated acid can cause a violent exothermic reaction that may splash the acid. Remember: 'Do as you oughta, add acid to water.'": "",
  "If you dilute 50 mL of 4 M NaOH to 200 mL, the final molarity is:": "",
  "2 M (half the original concentration)": "",
  "1 M (one quarter of the original value)": "",
  "4 M (the same as the original solution)": "",
  "8 M (double the original concentration)": "",
  "M1V1 = M2V2: (4 M)(50 mL) = M2(200 mL). M2 = 200/200 = 1 M.": "",
  "Dilution changes the concentration but not the:": "",
  "Volume of the overall solution in the flask": "",
  "Color of the solution in the flask container": "",
  "Total amount of solute (moles) present in it": "",
  "Temperature of the solution in the container": "",
  "Dilution does not change the total amount (moles) of solute. It only changes the concentration by increasing the total volume of solution.": "",
  "To make a solution less concentrated, you should:": "",
  "Add more solute to the existing solution volume": "",
  "Heat the solution to evaporate some of the solvent": "",
  "Add more solvent to the existing solution volume": "",
  "Cool the solution down to a lower temperature level": "",
  "Adding more solvent dilutes the solution, spreading the same amount of solute through a larger volume and decreasing the concentration.": "",
  "What is the definition of dilution?": "",
  "The process of adding more solute to increase concentration": "",
  "The process of adding solvent to decrease the concentration": "",
  "The process of removing solute by filtering the solution out": "",
  "The process of evaporating all the solvent from the solution": "",
  "Dilution is the process of reducing the concentration of a solution by adding more solvent. The total amount of solute remains constant.": "",
  "What does M1 represent in the dilution equation M1V1 = M2V2?": "",
  "The final molarity after the dilution is complete": "",
  "The initial molarity before the dilution begins": "",
  "The mass of solute in grams before the dilution": "",
  "The moles of solvent present before the dilution": "",
  "In M1V1 = M2V2, M1 represents the initial concentration (molarity) of the solution before dilution, and M2 is the final concentration after dilution.": "",
  "What does V2 represent in the dilution equation M1V1 = M2V2?": "",
  "The initial volume before the dilution process": "",
  "The final total volume after the dilution process": "",
  "The volume of solute added during the dilution step": "",
  "The volume of solute removed during the dilution": "",
  "V2 represents the final total volume of the solution after dilution. This includes both the original solution and the added solvent.": "",
  "What is a dilution factor?": "",
  "The temperature change that occurs during dilution process": "",
  "The ratio of final volume to initial volume in a dilution": "",
  "The mass of solvent that evaporates during the dilution": "",
  "The number of moles of solute lost during the dilution": "",
  "The dilution factor is the ratio of the final volume to the initial volume (V2/V1). A dilution factor of 10 means the solution was diluted to 10 times its original volume.": "",
  "Define the term 'serial dilution' in laboratory practice.": "",
  "A single step dilution performed one time in the laboratory": "",
  "A series of stepwise dilutions to achieve very low concentrations": "",
  "Adding all the solvent at once to achieve a final low concentration": "",
  "Evaporating solvent in steps to increase the final concentration": "",
  "Serial dilution is a technique where a solution is diluted step by step, with each step using the previous diluted solution. This allows precise preparation of extremely dilute solutions.": "",
  "What does 'exothermic' mean in the context of acid dilution safety?": "",
  "The process absorbs heat from the surrounding environment": "",
  "The process releases heat to the surrounding environment": "",
  "The process has no temperature change in the surroundings": "",
  "The process freezes the solution to a very low temperature": "",
  "Exothermic means heat is released. When concentrated acid is mixed with water, the process is highly exothermic. This is why acid must be added to water slowly to dissipate the heat safely.": "",
  "What is a 'stock solution' in the context of dilution?": "",
  "A very dilute solution that is ready for immediate experimental use": "",
  "A concentrated solution used as a starting point for making dilutions": "",
  "A solution with unknown concentration that needs to be tested first": "",
  "A saturated solution that cannot be diluted any further at all": "",
  "A stock solution is a concentrated solution from which more dilute solutions can be prepared by adding solvent. Labs keep stock solutions to efficiently make solutions at various concentrations.": "",
  "What does the term 'aliquot' mean in dilution procedures?": "",
  "The total volume of the final diluted solution in a flask": "",
  "A measured portion taken from a solution for further use": "",
  "The amount of solvent added to the solution for dilution": "",
  "The precipitate that forms at the bottom of the solution": "",
  "An aliquot is a precisely measured portion of a solution taken for analysis or further dilution. In serial dilution, an aliquot from each step is used to make the next dilution.": "",
  "What does 'inversely proportional' mean regarding concentration and volume in dilution?": "",
  "As volume increases the concentration also increases equally": "",
  "As volume increases the concentration decreases proportionally": "",
  "Volume and concentration always stay exactly the same value": "",
  "Volume and concentration have no mathematical relationship at all": "",
  "In dilution, concentration and volume are inversely proportional: when you double the volume, the concentration is halved, and vice versa (for a constant amount of solute).": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'volumetric flask' in dilution procedures?": "",
  "A flask used to heat solutions to their boiling point quickly": "",
  "A flask calibrated to hold a precise volume for making accurate solutions": "",
  "A flask used only for measuring the mass of solid chemicals": "",
  "A flask that changes color to indicate the concentration level": "",
  "A volumetric flask is precisely calibrated laboratory glassware designed to contain an exact volume of liquid at a specific temperature, commonly used for preparing solutions of known concentration.": "",
  "A student has 50 mL of 10 M HCl and needs to make 500 mL of 1 M HCl. Is this possible with the stock solution she has?": "",
  "No, because she would need at least 100 mL of stock solution": "",
  "Yes, because M1V1 = M2V2 gives (10)(50) = (1)(500) which balances": "",
  "No, because dilution can only reduce concentration by half at most": "",
  "Yes, but she would need to add more HCl solute to the water first": "",
  "Check: (10 M)(50 mL) = 500 = (1 M)(500 mL) = 500. The equation balances, so she needs exactly 50 mL of stock solution diluted to 500 mL total.": "",
  "A student accidentally adds too much water when diluting a solution. The target was 100 mL total but she now has 150 mL. What happened to the concentration?": "",
  "The concentration is higher than intended by a factor of 1.5": "",
  "The concentration is lower than intended because extra solvent was added": "",
  "The concentration is exactly what was intended since the solute is the same": "",
  "The concentration cannot be determined without knowing the temperature": "",
  "Adding more water than planned means V2 is larger than intended. Since M2 = M1V1/V2, a larger V2 results in a smaller (lower) concentration than the target.": "",
  "In a lab, a student needs to dilute 6 M H2SO4. She remembers the safety rule but cannot recall it exactly. Which procedure is correct?": "",
  "Pour water into the beaker of acid while stirring continuously": "",
  "Pour the acid slowly into a beaker of water while stirring gently": "",
  "Mix equal volumes of acid and water simultaneously in one step": "",
  "Heat the acid first to reduce its concentration before adding water": "",
  "Always add acid to water, never water to acid. The large volume of water absorbs the heat generated. Adding water to concentrated acid can cause dangerous spattering.": "",
  "A scientist performs a 1:10 serial dilution three times starting with a 1 M solution. What is the final concentration?": "",
  "0.1 M after three serial dilution steps": "",
  "0.01 M after three serial dilution steps": "",
  "0.001 M after three serial dilution steps": "",
  "0.0001 M after three serial dilution steps": "",
  "Each 1:10 dilution divides the concentration by 10. Starting at 1 M: after step 1 = 0.1 M, step 2 = 0.01 M, step 3 = 0.001 M.": "",
  "A student is asked to prepare 250 mL of 0.5 M NaCl from a 2 M stock. How much stock solution does the student need?": "",
